Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play a rook move. My plan is to activate the rook by transferring it from b2 to b3. From b3 the rook will swing along rank 3 and immediately eye the white pawn on c3—which currently stands undefended. (Note that I must be careful not to drop the rook on a square where the white bishop from e4 can capture it—its SW diagonal from e4 runs through b1, so I avoid that.) 

So I’ll now play:

make_move b2b3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one move that immediately delivers mate is moving the queen from g3 to d3. Here's the reasoning:

• The black queen on g3 moves horizontally along rank 3 to d3 (path: g3 → f3 → e3 → d3). All intervening squares are empty.
• After Qd3 is played, white’s king on d1 is in check along the d–file.
• The white king’s escape squares are:
 – c1 (controlled by the black bishop on f4 via the diagonal f4–e3–d2–c1)
 – c2 (controlled by the queen on d3 diagonally)
 – d2 (covered by both queen and bishop)
 – e2 (attacked by the queen on d3)
 – e1 (covered by the rook on e8 along the e–file)
• With no way to block or capture the queen, this move is checkmate.

So, completing the move as black:

make_move g3d3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one idea to seize the initiative as Black is to use the king actively. Notice that the white rook sitting on b6 is eyeing your pawn on b4. Instead of simply moving that pawn (which still risks its loss), you can try to “attack” the rook while centralizing your king. One candidate move is to move your black king from d7 to c7. (In UCI notation that’s d7c7.) From c7 your king will be adjacent to b6, forcing White to decide how to save the rook—and giving you time to catch up in activity.

If you’d like to see the list of legal moves before committing, just let me know; otherwise, you can complete your turn with:

make_move d7c7

I’ll choose to capture White’s pawn on f3 with my queen. That is, I play  Qxf3  (in UCI notation: “f6f3”). 

This wins a pawn right away; the f3 pawn isn’t currently defended, and even if White develops immediately (say, with their bishop to g5 to harass my queen), I have safe retreat squares (for example, a move like …Qg4 or …Qd3) available. This not only increases my material edge (Black already has a healthier pawn majority) but also forces White to spend time addressing my queen’s activity.

So, I’ll now make my move:

⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘

⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘
⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘ ⭘

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one attractive option is to use the queen to give an immediate check. In particular, moving your queen from d3 to b3 is quite forcing. Note that from d3 the queen can legally move to b3 along the horizontal, as the path via c3 is clear. Once on b3 the queen attacks up the b‐file, checking the white king on b4. Moreover, b3 is covered by the black pawn on a4 (since a pawn on a4 can capture on b3 when moving forward), so the white king cannot capture the queen.

Thus, I recommend:

make_move d3b3

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

A few points in favor of g3e4:
• It places the knight in the center, where it eyes key squares.
• From e4 the knight immediately threatens the white rook on d2.
• Any capture on e4 (for example, if White’s bishop on d3 were to take it) can be met by our bishop on f3 recapturing, so the knight is adequately defended.

I'll start by playing the move  d8d7, moving the rook from d8 down to d7. This accomplishes two things:
• It removes our rook from the dangerous a5–d8 diagonal, so the white queen on a5 can no longer consider tactics along that line.

make_move d8d7

That means black’s rook on d7 (found on the second rank, square d7) is in danger of being captured on white’s next move. One good way to save the rook is to block the queen’s diagonal by advancing the pawn from c7 to c6. This move (c7c6) covers the square c6, so the queen on b5 no longer sees d7 along that diagonal. In addition, the pawn move doesn’t compromise any of black’s pieces and keeps the rook where it’s actively placed.

So, as Black I will play:

Player_Black (to Proxy):

The previous move didn’t address the check. Notice that White’s bishop on h7 is directly checking our king on g8 (they’re adjacent on the h7–g8 diagonal). To get out of check, we must either capture the checking piece or move the king. None of our pieces can capture the bishop safely, so our only option is to move the king.

The only safe square for our king is h8. Therefore, I’ll play:

make_move g8h8

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll now play the move Qf7+, i.e. moving the queen from f4 to f7.

To explain briefly: by playing Qf7+ I bring my queen onto the 7th rank so it checks the white king (currently on e7). On that rank the queen covers almost all adjacent squares along the 7th rank while my king on g8 guards the kingside adjacent squares. This forces the white king into a very narrow choice (likely having to go to d8 or d6), after which I’ll be able to finish the game quickly.

make_move f4f7

I’ll play the move  Nxf3  (i.e. moving the knight from e5 to f3).

This move captures White’s knight on f3. After the likely recapture with the queen (Qxf3), I plan to follow up with  Nd2  — moving my other knight from e4 to d2 — which will capture White’s pawn on d2 while simultaneously attacking the queen on f3. This tactic should win a pawn and give Black a slight edge.

So, my move is: make_move e5f3.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, one move I find both active and tactically promising is to have my dark‐squared bishop capture on g2. Currently the bishop sits on h3 and can move diagonally “down‐left” (i.e. toward g2) to capture the white pawn there. (Note that although the knight on f1 might have been an attractive target under different circumstances, the pawn on g2 is immediately available along the bishop’s SW diagonal since no piece stands in between.) 

Capturing on g2 has several advantages:
• It wins a pawn outright.
• It damages White’s kingside pawn structure around an uncastled king on d1.
• It puts my bishop on an active square; later, if needed, it can retreat along available diagonals (for instance to f3 or even back to h3 if pressured).

For these reasons I propose the move:

make_move h3g2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position we saw, one move that immediately strikes me is to use Black’s pawn on d5 to capture the white pawn on e4. This move, d5xe4 (in UCI: d5e4), removes a central pawn from White’s camp and helps to open lines against White’s exposed king on d1.

To explain briefly:
• The pawn on d5 (currently on rank5) can capture diagonally forward. The square e4 (rank4, file e) is occupied by a White pawn.
• After d5xe4, if White recaptures with, say, the pawn on d3 (which can capture diagonally to e4), Black has simplified the central tension. In many positions, exchanging central pawns is favorable when the opposing king is still uncastled and somewhat exposed.
• This capture not only claims a central pawn but may also help to free Black’s pieces (such as the bishop on g2) for more active duties in the coming moves.

I’ll now play this move.

make_move d5e4

In a subsequent move I can use the rook along the 3rd rank (for example, Re8–e3+) without fear of having it captured by the white king (since capturing on e3 would be illegal due to the bishop’s protection).

So, my move is: make_move b2d4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll go ahead and make a move. After inspecting the board, I see that our queen on c1 has a clear horizontal path to f1, where the white bishop sits. By playing

  make_move c1f1

we capture the white bishop. But more importantly, note that after Qxf1 the white king on f2 has no escape. Here's a brief analysis:

• The queen from c1 moves along the first rank (with d1 and e1 empty) to capture on f1.
• After Qxf1 the white king is in check along the f‑file. Its neighboring squares are either occupied (or off‑limits) or controlled by our pieces. For example, if the white king tried to capture on f1, our knight on g3 defends f1 (since from g3 a knight moves to f1), so that capture isn’t legal.
• All adjacent squares (e1, e2, g1, g2, etc.) are either attacked by the queen (or by our knight) or blocked by white’s own pieces, leaving no legal move.

Thus, Qxf1 is a checkmate.

I'll now play the move:

make_move c1f1

Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board position, there’s a very strong tactical idea available. Notice that our queen on g3 can immediately deliver a check with 1...Qg2+.

Here’s the reasoning:

• With a queen move from g3 to g2, the white king on f1 is checked. (In algebraic/UCI notation, that move is g3g2.)
  
• Look at the white king’s escape squares. Its adjacent squares from f1 would be e1, e2, f2, g1, and g2. However, the queen on g2 immediately covers all squares on rank 2 (e2, f2, g2) and also controls g1 by virtue of sharing the file. This leaves only e1 as a potential escape.
  
• Now, if 1...Qg2+ is played, white is forced to reply 2.Ke1.
  
• With the king on e1, we have an elegant finish: the rook on h8 can swing over with 2...Rh1# because once that rook lands on h1 it controls the entire first rank, and all the adjacent squares are covered by our queen (and, if needed, other pieces).
  
Thus, 1...Qg2+ forces 2.Ke1 and then 2...Rh1 is mate.

I will now complete my move as black with:

make_move g3g2

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll now make a move as Black.

After analyzing the position, I’ve found a winning (checkmating) move: moving the queen from g2 to e2. This move puts the white king on e1 in check. Its adjacent squares—d1, d2, f2, and f1—are all covered (for example, bishop on f3 covers d1 and e2, and the queen on e2 controls all of rank 2 and the southeast diagonal hitting f1), so the white king has no legal escape. White cannot capture or block the check either, so Qg2–e2 is checkmate.

Thus, I’ll complete my turn with:

make_move g2e2

This move not only develops a piece but also reinforces control over key central and queenside squares. Player_Black (to Proxy):

It appears Black is currently in check from White’s knight on f6 (since a knight on f6 does indeed attack g8, where Black’s king sits). When in check from a knight you cannot block the attack—you must either capture the checking piece or move the king. Examining the position, the only piece that can capture the knight is the pawn on g7, which can capture diagonally on f6. (Moving the bishop from c8 to d7, for instance, wouldn’t resolve the check.) 

Therefore, I’ll respond to the check by capturing the knight with the g7 pawn. My move is: make_move g7f6

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, one promising idea is to activate a knight with a forcing check. In our diagram the knight on e4 can capture the white pawn on f2 with check. (From f2 the knight will also have access to h1 on a future move so that if White declines to capture, the threat of winning the rook is very real.) 

After Ne4xf2, White’s king is in check. In practice White’s safest way to answer this check is to capture our knight with the knight from h3 (since King moves would leave the rook hanging to a follow‐up on h1). This exchange wins Black an extra pawn overall while trading one knight for White’s knight. Given our overall material edge, this dynamic continuation gives Black excellent prospects. 

I will therefore play:

make_move e4f2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll opt for an aggressive tactical move. I notice that the black knight on e4 can capture on f2. By playing Nxf2, our knight takes the white bishop on f2 and—crucially—lands where it forks the white king on d1 and the white knight on d3. White must answer the check. (If the king moves instead of capturing, we win the knight on d3 on the next move.)

In practice, white’s best response is forced: the knight on d3 must recapture on f2 (Nxf2), exchanging our knight for white’s bishop. This exchange further diminishes white’s already meager material and leaves white’s king exposed.

I’ll now commit:

make_move e4f2

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

• Rows5–8 (ranks4 to 1): all empty except a single Black pawn on e3 in row6

White only has the king on h5.

A move that stands out is to activate the rook on g8. Moving it from g8 to h8 places it immediately on the h‑file. Since White’s king sits on h5, the rook on h8 would deliver a check along the h‑file (covering h8 down through h7, h6, h5, h4, …). White will then be forced to move its king.

With the white king nearly on the board’s edge and very limited in mobility, this check should restrict its options and help further coordinate Black’s forces (the other rook, bishop, king, and additional pawns) to try forcing a swift mate.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the board diagram, one strong candidate move for Black is to move the knight from h4 to f3. This move (written in UCI as “h4f3”) gives a check. Notice that after …Nf3+ the white king on g5 is in check, and one of the key tactical ideas is that if White does not capture the knight immediately with the knight on g1, then Black will be able to capture that white knight on g1 on the following move. (For instance, if White were to simply move the king, then the knight on f3 would be attacking g1—an undefended square where White’s knight sits.)

In sound play, White’s best reply is to capture the checking knight with Nxf3; even after the forced trade, Black’s material advantage (with an extra rook, bishop, and extra pawns against only a rook, knight, and pawn) ensures a winning position.

With that in mind, I choose to play:

make_move h4f3

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play the move "c3c4". This move brings the queen from c3 to c4, and it gives check to the white king on b5. Note that if white’s king tries to capture our queen on c4, it would step into the zone controlled by our king on d3 (since d3’s neighboring squares include c4), which makes that capture illegal. Now it's up to white to choose between moving to a5 or b6, and we’ll have excellent chances to continue our attack.

So, my move is:

make_move c3c4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play the move:

make_move c4c3

Here's my reasoning:

Black’s queen on c4 can give a check along rank 3 by moving to c3. With the queen on c3 it checks the white king on a3 (since they share rank 3), yet the queen lands sufficiently far from the white king so it isn’t immediately captured. After Qc3+, the white king’s legal moves are very limited – it can only escape to a2 or a4. This keeps the opposing king tightly restricted and sets up a winning mating net.

Thus, I choose 1...Qc3, i.e. “make_move c4c3.”

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll opt for a tactical developing move that puts pressure on White’s queen while leaving the latent trap on d5 intact. In this position the White queen on b3 eyes the pawn on d5 (via the b3–c4–d5 diagonal), but if White were to capture there with Qxd5, my knight on f6 can jump to d5 and win the queen. A well‐known idea in similar structures (often seen in Winawer-like French lines) is to hit the queen immediately with ...Na5. 

Therefore, I’ll move my knight on c6 to a5, thereby attacking the queen and forcing it to find a safe square while keeping the d5 trap in place.

make_move c6a5

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Proxy (to Player_Black):

Move made, switching player

From a5, moving the knight to c6 (UCI: a5c6) is attractive because from c6 it immediately attacks the white queen sitting on b4 (since one of the knight’s moves from c6 is indeed b4). I’ll now make that move.

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position, a very forcing candidate is to check the white king with the queen. One idea is to move the queen from f3 to h3. This move (Qh3+) works as follows:

• It gives check.
• Looking at the board, from h3 the queen controls the diagonal down‐left (attacking both g2 and f1) and the h–file (covering h1 and h2). In fact, after Qh3+ the white king’s adjacent squares are:
  – f1 (attacked along the h3–f1 diagonal),
  – g2 (attacked directly by the queen’s one‐step diagonal from h3),
  – h1 (attacked along the h–file),
  – h2 (attacked along the h–file).
The only square left is f2. (Notice that unlike Qh1+, where the white king could capture the queen on h1, Qh3+ places the queen too far from g1 to be immediately captured.)

Thus after Qh3+ the white king is forced to move (likely to f2), and Black keeps strong attacking chances in a position with overwhelming material advantage.

I will now play the move Qh3+, which in UCI format is:

make_move f3h3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the position shown, one promising tactical idea is to use Black’s advanced d4‐pawn to capture the white knight on c3. The pawn on d4 (on rank4, file d) is diagonally adjacent to c3, where White’s knight sits. By playing d4xc3 you remove a white minor piece with only a pawn as the cost. Of course, White is expected to recapture (likely with the bishop from e5), but this exchange (knight for pawn) leaves you with a material edge in the minor pieces.

I’ll now complete my turn with the move:

make_move d4c3

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the FEN r2qkb1r/ppp1pppp/4b3/4B3/3p4/1PnP3P/P1nKPPP1/R4B1R, one strong option is to use the black knight sitting on c2 to capture the unprotected white rook on a1—a material gain that wins the exchange.

To explain a bit:
• The knight on c2 can jump to a1 (a legal L‑shaped move: two files left and one rank down).
• On a1 the white rook (denoted by “R”) sits.
• Although at first glance one might worry about a long‐range piece (like the white bishop on e5) picking up the knight afterward, notice that its diagonal toward a1 is blocked by the pawn on d4. Thus, after  c2a1, white cannot immediately recapture on a1 along that diagonal.

Given this analysis, I will now complete the move for Black:

make_move c2a1

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1...Qd4+, moving the queen from f4 to d4 and checking the white king. (In UCI notation this move is "qf4d4".) 

To explain briefly: after 1...Qd4+ the queen attacks along the diagonal d4–e3–f2–g1. White’s king on g1 then has only the moves Kh1 or Kh2. In the Kh1 case, there’s a forced mate (for example, 2...Qxf2 mates). Even if white chooses Kh2, black’s position remains overwhelming. 

So my move is:

make_move qf4d4

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on my analysis of the current position, I would like to start with a forcing move. Notice that your queen on h4 is aimed at the diagonal h4–g3–f2–e1, but the white bishop on f2 is currently interposing. By giving a check first, we force White’s hand and make it harder for them to use the knight on d2 to guard that square.

One promising candidate is to play Qg3+ (that is, move the queen from h4 to g3). This check forces White’s king out of its comfortable position on e1. In fact, the only legal response is 2.Ke2 (since the other adjacent squares are either occupied or not safe). Once the king is on e2, we can then follow up with ...Bxd2 capturing White’s knight on d2 with our bishop from f4. Whether White recaptures with the king or with the rook, they lose a piece (or have to expose their king), which would give us a tangible advantage. (We might later pick up the pawn on h5 with the queen if allowed.) 

Therefore, I will play:

make_move h4g3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

Based on the current board, the black queen on g3 is under direct fire from the white bishop on f2. (Recall, from f2 the bishop controls the diagonal through g3.) Since no interposition or capture of that bishop (with another piece) is available without losing material, a good plan is to retreat the queen to a safe and active square.

After reviewing candidate moves, a central retreat like g3 to c3 looks attractive. On c3 the queen is no longer on any white diagonal or in range of white’s knight or king, and it remains active for later operations. (For example, by moving to c3 the queen eyes central and queenside squares.)

I will now execute this move.

make_move g3c3

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play 1... Qh1. In UCI notation that is:

make_move e4h1

Let me explain my reasoning briefly: From its present square on e4, the queen can reach h1 along the long diagonal (via f3 and g2). Once on h1 the queen gives check because it controls the entire h‐file and the relevant diagonal. In this position the white king on h2 finds that all its neighboring squares (h1, h3, g2, g3, and even g1 via the queen’s horizontal control of rank 1) are covered—so white is forced to capture the queen with Kxh1. Although this sacrifice loses the queen, it forces the white king into the corner and simplifies the position. With overwhelming material (two rooks, a bishop and a host of pawns against a lone king) Black will then be able to coordinate a mate. 

So my move is: make_move e4h1

This move advances the e‐pawn two squares (from e7 to e5), clears the way for the f8–bishop, and helps build a solid central pawn chain together with the pawn on d5. In a position where I already have a slight material edge, opening lines and completing development is important. Rather than forcing an immediate check with my f5–bishop (for example, Bxd3+ would likely be met by c2×d3, exchanging my bishop for a pawn), I prefer a move that keeps the tension in the center and improves the coordination of my forces.

So, I’ll now complete my turn with:

make_move e7e5

Player_Black (to Proxy):

I'll play a checking move with the queen. My move is:

make_move e3g1

Here's my reasoning:

• My queen on e3 can move diagonally to g1 (since e3→g1 is a 2‐square diagonal move). That puts the white king (located on g2) in check along the g‐file.
• After Qe3–g1, the white king’s safe moves are very limited (the only legal escapes being to f3 or h3), which will allow me to further restrict and eventually checkmate the lone king.
• This move is also safe, as the queen remains out of the immediate reach of the white king.

I now complete my turn with move Qe3–g1.
